        {
            "id": "9dc8b8a952d94f9aa976d",
            "questionText": "A radio antenna emits electromagnetic waves at a frequency of $!$98.5 \\ MHz$!$. These waves travel to a receiver located $!$50 \\ km$!$ away. Due to atmospheric conditions, there's a slight delay in the arrival time of the signal. If the delay is measured to be $!$5 \\ \\mu s$!$, what is the phase difference between the emitted signal and the received signal at the receiver, considering the electromagnetic waves are produced by accelerating charges?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "fe48263f55e248308983f",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by determining the number of cycles that occur during the delay. Identify the correct formula that relates the frequency $!$f$!$ and the delay $!$\\Delta t$!$ to the total number of cycles.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ee8bb1a6-fd07-4f51-81ae-e388a2828537"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$N = f \\times \\Delta t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$N = f / \\Delta t$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$N = \\Delta t / f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "6bcff4550d99452abd902",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, use the formula from the previous step by multiplying the frequency $!$f = 98.5 \\times 10^6\\,Hz$!$ with the delay $!$\\Delta t = 5 \\times 10^{-6}\\,s$!$ to determine the total number of cycles. What do you get?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "492.5"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "cycles",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ee8bb1a6-fd07-4f51-81ae-e388a2828537"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "42eebc6a00e041e392762",
                    "stepText": "Next, note that only the fractional part of the cycles affects the phase difference. To convert this fractional cycle into a phase difference in radians, identify the correct multiplication factor from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0c3ff372-9bd8-4961-9294-ab325dbdc20e"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\phi = 2\\pi \\times (\\text{fractional part})$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\phi = \\pi \\times (\\text{fractional part})$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\phi = 360 \\times (\\text{fractional part})$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "bd8531088c1843e4941e7",
                    "stepText": "Finally, compute the phase difference by multiplying the fractional part of the cycles (which is the decimal part from step 2) by the conversion factor you identified. What is the phase difference in radians? (It is approximately equal to multiplying 0.5 by $!$2\\pi$!$)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3.1416"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "radians",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0c3ff372-9bd8-4961-9294-ab325dbdc20e"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
